WEBVTT

00:01.827 --> 00:05.135
Previously onYoung Sheldon...You can't be my lab assistant.

00:05.179 --> 00:06.354
There's a wait list of students

00:06.397 --> 00:08.356
and I just can't give you
special treatment.

00:08.399 --> 00:10.271
Not with that attitude.

00:10.314 --> 00:11.576
[phone rings]

00:11.620 --> 00:13.317
Hello?

00:13.361 --> 00:14.666
Can I be your lab assistant?

00:14.710 --> 00:17.017
If I say yes, will you
please stop hounding me?

00:17.060 --> 00:19.149
Absolutely.Fine, you win.

00:20.237 --> 00:21.543
I understand my role here.

00:21.586 --> 00:24.111
In fact, I noticed a flaw
in your reaction rate,

00:24.154 --> 00:26.069
but I kept it to myself
because I know my place.

00:26.113 --> 00:28.115
What is it?Nice try.

00:28.158 --> 00:29.551
LINKLETTER:
Fire!

00:29.594 --> 00:30.900
Fire!

00:30.943 --> 00:32.902
Was it too much oxygen
in the reagents?

00:32.945 --> 00:35.209
See, you didn't need
my help after all.

00:39.952 --> 00:43.086
ADULT SHELDON:
My role as Dr. Linkletter's
lab assistant

00:43.130 --> 00:44.696
was progressing nicely.

00:44.740 --> 00:47.917
I had mastered operating
the manual particle collector,

00:47.960 --> 00:49.614
aka a broom.

00:49.658 --> 00:51.921
I may not always recognize

00:51.964 --> 00:53.923
sarcasm,
but I sure know how to use it.

00:53.966 --> 00:55.098
Sheldon,

00:55.142 --> 00:56.969
I've hit a bit of a roadblock

00:57.013 --> 00:58.928
with the solar
neutrino detector.

00:58.971 --> 01:00.582
Why don't you come have a look?

01:00.625 --> 01:04.064
Are you saying you would like meto take part in your experiment?

01:04.107 --> 01:07.284
Well, I think a fresh set
of eyes might be helpful.

01:07.328 --> 01:10.113
Because my previous observationsproved correct?

01:10.157 --> 01:12.115
Yes.

01:12.159 --> 01:14.596
And had you listened to me, the
lab wouldn't have caught fire?

01:14.639 --> 01:15.988
Yes.

01:16.032 --> 01:17.468
So just to be clear,
at the tender age of 11,

01:17.512 --> 01:19.949
I'll be officially participatingin an academic study.

01:19.992 --> 01:21.255
Will you do it or not?

01:21.298 --> 01:22.995
Absolutely. Here you go.

01:23.039 --> 01:24.954
What am I supposed to do
with this?

01:24.997 --> 01:27.391
Well, if you can't figure thatout, no wonder you need my help.

01:29.698 --> 01:32.614
♪ Nobody else
is stronger than I am ♪

01:32.657 --> 01:35.182
♪ Yesterday I moved a mountain

01:35.225 --> 01:38.533
♪ I bet I could be your hero

01:38.576 --> 01:41.188
♪ I am a mighty little man

01:41.231 --> 01:44.669
♪ I am a mighty little man.♪

01:49.500 --> 01:50.632
Do we have another
hair dryer?

01:50.675 --> 01:52.112
This one broke.

01:52.155 --> 01:54.157
Just use a towel.

01:54.201 --> 01:55.637
So my hair can look like yours?

01:55.680 --> 01:57.291
I don't think so.

01:58.379 --> 01:59.989
Go look in the garage.

02:00.032 --> 02:01.164
Thank you.

02:06.213 --> 02:07.997
I like my hair.

02:08.040 --> 02:10.173
ADULT SHELDON: I may have been
part of an academic study,

02:10.217 --> 02:11.740
but I wasn't the only Cooper

02:11.783 --> 02:13.698
on the verge of making
a great discovery.

02:15.178 --> 02:16.397
Sheldon's tests.

02:18.225 --> 02:20.662
[heavenly choir sings]

02:22.054 --> 02:23.491
I'm gonna be rich.

02:23.534 --> 02:25.667
[knocking]MARY: Missy, ten minutes.

02:25.710 --> 02:27.147
MISSY:
Okay.

02:27.190 --> 02:28.670
[clears throat]

02:33.457 --> 02:35.546
♪

02:36.547 --> 02:37.592
Whatcha looking at?

02:37.635 --> 02:40.377
Uh, just Pastor Jeffand Mrs. Sparks.

02:40.421 --> 02:42.249
They were out there
the other day, too.

02:42.292 --> 02:44.076
Oh.

02:44.120 --> 02:45.687
How come you don't go with them?

02:47.123 --> 02:48.690
They didn't invite me.

02:48.733 --> 02:50.213
Ouch.

02:50.257 --> 02:51.432
Rough start to your day.

02:51.475 --> 02:53.390
[exhales]

02:55.087 --> 02:56.524
So, the problemthat I'm running into

02:56.567 --> 02:57.699
is I can't getthe inner sphere

02:57.742 --> 03:00.223
to remain suspendedin the buffer liquid.

03:00.267 --> 03:02.269
Have you tried wrapping
the sphere in copper wire?

03:02.312 --> 03:04.358
I did,but it just slips out.

03:04.401 --> 03:07.056
Perhaps we could suspend it
in some sort of sleeve.

03:07.099 --> 03:09.232
That would prevent lightfrom getting through.

03:09.276 --> 03:11.060
Hmm.

03:11.103 --> 03:12.714
I wonder if my thinking
would be more effective

03:12.757 --> 03:14.368
if I had a beard to stroke.

03:14.411 --> 03:17.327
It's one of the few aspects of
puberty I'm looking forward to.

03:19.155 --> 03:21.070
GEORGE JR.:
Hey, Tam.

03:21.113 --> 03:22.724
Hey.What if I told you

03:22.767 --> 03:25.074
you didn't have to study
for your chemistry test tonight?

03:25.117 --> 03:26.510
Why?

03:26.554 --> 03:28.077
'Cause I found this.

03:28.120 --> 03:29.557
TAM:
Cool.

03:29.600 --> 03:32.299
But how do you know
we're gonna get the same test?

03:32.342 --> 03:35.563
I checked-- we've been taking
the same ones all year.

03:35.606 --> 03:38.087
And teachers call uslazy?

03:38.130 --> 03:39.306
I know.

03:39.349 --> 03:41.569
Well, thank you.

03:41.612 --> 03:44.093
Hold on now.
I ain't just givin' it away.

03:44.136 --> 03:45.573
How much?

03:45.616 --> 03:47.270
Five bucks.

03:47.314 --> 03:48.663
It's worth it.

03:48.706 --> 03:50.578
If I get another B,
my mom will kill me.

03:50.621 --> 03:52.841
Hey, I don't just sell tests.

03:52.884 --> 03:55.583
I bring families together.

03:55.626 --> 03:57.585
♪ Take the Lord,
praise the Lord... ♪

03:57.628 --> 03:59.195
Get this.

03:59.239 --> 04:00.370
I drove past

04:00.414 --> 04:01.763
the Methodist church
and you know

04:01.806 --> 04:03.243
what the sign out front said?

04:03.286 --> 04:04.766
What?

04:04.809 --> 04:08.552
"Friendship, pirate ship,
try the best ship-- worship."

04:08.596 --> 04:09.814
Clever.

04:09.858 --> 04:12.295
That was our sign last year!
I wrote that!

04:12.339 --> 04:14.384
Isn't the most important thing

04:14.428 --> 04:16.821
that it might get more people
to go to church?

04:16.865 --> 04:19.128
But whoever did it
has the sin of stealing

04:19.171 --> 04:21.217
on their soul now,
so at least there's that.

04:22.218 --> 04:23.698
There you go.

04:24.829 --> 04:26.266
Oh, um...

04:26.309 --> 04:27.267
I saw

04:27.310 --> 04:29.181
you and Brenda Sparks

04:29.225 --> 04:31.662
out for a walk this mornin'.

04:32.663 --> 04:34.578
That's fun.
Yeah.

04:34.622 --> 04:36.580
Nice way to start the day.

04:36.624 --> 04:37.538
Yeah. Um...

04:37.581 --> 04:38.669
I'd go with George,

04:38.713 --> 04:40.192
but he's a gym teacher,

04:40.236 --> 04:43.195
and as a group,
they're not much for walkin'.

04:44.240 --> 04:46.851
Well, you keep asking,
maybe he'll come around.

04:48.505 --> 04:50.290
Good idea, thank you.

04:50.333 --> 04:52.857
It's not just
witty church signs up here.

04:54.468 --> 04:55.730
[sighs]

04:55.773 --> 04:57.819
I never thought a sphere
suspended in mineral oil

04:57.862 --> 04:59.386
could be so exciting.

04:59.429 --> 05:01.170
Eight minutes and
it hasn't moved.

05:01.213 --> 05:02.389
So far so good.

05:02.432 --> 05:04.478
Oh, boy,
my heart is pounding.

05:04.521 --> 05:06.175
I hope I don't turn
into an adrenaline junkie.

05:06.218 --> 05:08.220
What's going
on in there?

05:08.264 --> 05:10.658
This is a prototype
of a solar neutrino detector.

05:10.701 --> 05:12.486
We need to keep
the sphere suspended

05:12.529 --> 05:14.314
precisely
in the scintillator.

05:14.357 --> 05:15.619
Speaking of scintillating...

05:15.663 --> 05:17.578
No.
Sorry.

05:18.753 --> 05:20.363
Darn it.

05:20.407 --> 05:22.322
Ah, the oil must've
dissolved the adhesive.

05:22.365 --> 05:23.366
Well...

05:23.410 --> 05:24.715
ready to hit the road?

05:24.759 --> 05:27.327
Please, not yet.
We're so close to cracking this.

05:27.370 --> 05:29.633
Just ten more minutes?

05:29.677 --> 05:30.895
Fine.

05:30.939 --> 05:33.594
Oh, boy.
Yes!

05:33.637 --> 05:35.509
ADULT SHELDON:
I wasn't even at that school,

05:35.552 --> 05:37.859
and I was still boosting
its grade point average.

05:37.902 --> 05:39.382
You got biology?

05:39.426 --> 05:40.862
Depends. You got money?

05:40.905 --> 05:43.647
Yeah.I got biology.

05:47.608 --> 05:50.698
Perhaps we could create some
sort of a cocoon to suspend it.

05:50.741 --> 05:52.874
Out of wire?Or nylon.

05:52.917 --> 05:55.442
But I wouldn't know
how to weave it around a sphere.

05:55.485 --> 05:57.444
I'm not a genius,
but it sounds to me

05:57.487 --> 05:59.924
like what y'all are talking
about is, uh, crochet.

05:59.968 --> 06:02.492
I suppose we are.

06:02.536 --> 06:05.626
Because with crochet, you can
make all kinds of shapes.

06:05.669 --> 06:07.367
Intriguing.

06:07.410 --> 06:10.457
Hell, I even crocheted
a cover for Jolene.

06:10.500 --> 06:11.588
I'm sorry?

06:11.632 --> 06:13.285
That's my bowling ball.

06:13.329 --> 06:15.592
She likes to name inanimate
objects-- it's odd.

06:15.636 --> 06:16.985
Or whimsically charming.

06:17.028 --> 06:19.727
Connie, would you help us
detect solar neutrinos?

06:19.770 --> 06:21.468
Really?

06:21.511 --> 06:24.253
You-you-you want me to be
a part of your science thing?

06:24.296 --> 06:25.428
Indeed.

06:26.603 --> 06:28.431
Well...

06:28.475 --> 06:30.694
sure, why not.[chuckles]

06:30.738 --> 06:31.869
Excellent.

06:31.913 --> 06:34.394
ADULT SHELDON:
And just like that,

06:34.437 --> 06:38.354
my meemaw had been seduced
by the siren call of science.

06:38.398 --> 06:40.748
But before we unravel
the secrets of the universe,

06:40.791 --> 06:42.314
I'm gonna hit the john.

06:42.358 --> 06:43.838
Oh... of course.

06:49.670 --> 06:50.671
MARY: And bless the hands
that prepared it.

06:50.714 --> 06:51.672
Amen.

06:51.715 --> 06:53.021
Amen.
Amen.

06:53.064 --> 06:54.501
Where is everyone?

06:54.544 --> 06:55.502
Georgie's out and Sheldon's

06:55.545 --> 06:56.807
at the university with Meemaw.

06:56.851 --> 06:58.461
A lot of pressure on me
to keep things fun.

06:58.505 --> 06:59.984
MARY:
Hey, I was thinking

07:00.028 --> 07:02.639
after dinner, maybe you and I
could go out for a walk.

07:04.032 --> 07:05.642
Why?

07:05.686 --> 07:07.905
Pastor Jeff and Brenda have
been doing it, might be nice.

07:07.949 --> 07:10.386
So go with them.

07:10.430 --> 07:12.736
They didn't invite her.
She was all upset about it.

07:12.780 --> 07:13.824
[clears throat]

07:13.868 --> 07:15.043
Well, you get left out

07:15.086 --> 07:16.436
and I get punished?

07:16.479 --> 07:18.742
A walk with your wife
is punishment?

07:18.786 --> 07:20.657
You're up, say somethin' fun.

07:20.701 --> 07:22.529
I think Pastor Jeff
and Mrs. Sparks

07:22.572 --> 07:24.400
might be talking about Billy.

07:24.444 --> 07:25.836
What's going on with Billy?

07:25.880 --> 07:27.795
He's been getting
in trouble at school.

07:27.838 --> 07:29.536
How is that fun?

07:29.579 --> 07:31.712
It's gossip. Gossip's fun.

07:32.843 --> 07:34.715
Poor thing.

07:34.758 --> 07:37.892
Brenda did say he was
having trouble adjusting.

07:37.935 --> 07:40.895
Maybe I should see
if she's doing okay later.

07:40.938 --> 07:42.984
Great idea.
I'm not walking, good job.

07:45.943 --> 07:48.119
So what am I
making this thing out of?

07:48.163 --> 07:49.904
We were using wire,
but that might be

07:49.947 --> 07:51.514
difficult to
crochet with.

07:51.558 --> 07:53.908
Oh, please,
I could crochet barbed wire

07:53.951 --> 07:55.779
with a chopstick if I had to.

07:55.823 --> 07:57.128
I admire your bravado.

07:57.172 --> 07:58.434
In this case,

07:58.478 --> 08:00.001
isn't it the feminine,
"bravada"?

08:00.044 --> 08:01.655
I've never heard
the term "bravada."

08:01.698 --> 08:02.786
Let's just go
with "chutzpah."

08:02.830 --> 08:04.658
What's chutzpah?It's like moxie.

08:04.701 --> 08:05.746
Oh, I do like moxie.

08:05.789 --> 08:07.095
I admire your moxie.

08:07.138 --> 08:08.662
However, I believe
that nylon thread

08:08.705 --> 08:10.011
would be the best choice.

08:10.054 --> 08:11.795
True, it's chemically inert
and would allow

08:11.839 --> 08:13.014
more light to pass through.

08:13.057 --> 08:14.537
Nylon thread.

08:14.581 --> 08:15.712
Done.

08:15.756 --> 08:17.845
Brava. That one
I know is a word.

08:17.888 --> 08:19.107
MEEMAW:
Can I ask...

08:19.150 --> 08:20.761
why exactly are we looking

08:20.804 --> 08:22.458
for solar neutrinos?

08:22.502 --> 08:24.721
Other experiments have only
seen about half the neutrinos

08:24.765 --> 08:25.940
coming from the Sun.

08:25.983 --> 08:27.507
And we'd like to
figure out why.

08:27.550 --> 08:29.117
And what happens if we do?

08:29.160 --> 08:30.727
They will tell us
what kind of nuclear reactions

08:30.771 --> 08:31.772
are going on there.

08:31.815 --> 08:33.469
In the Sun?

08:33.513 --> 08:35.036
Yes.

08:35.079 --> 08:36.864
That's so far-- how?

08:36.907 --> 08:39.562
Neutrinos are made deep
within the core of the Sun.

08:39.606 --> 08:41.129
They have to go
over a hundred times

08:41.172 --> 08:42.870
the radius of Earth
just to get out.

08:42.913 --> 08:44.741
Mm, kind of like
how you can drive

08:44.785 --> 08:47.004
all day and still
be in Texas.

08:47.048 --> 08:48.702
Exactly, then they have
to travel another

08:48.745 --> 08:50.617
93 million miles
just to get here.

08:50.660 --> 08:51.922
Huh.Neutrinos are essentially

08:51.966 --> 08:54.490
direct messengers
from the center of the Sun.

08:54.534 --> 08:56.623
That's why we're
building the prototype.

08:56.666 --> 08:58.799
And I get to be a part of it?

08:58.842 --> 08:59.756
You do.

08:59.800 --> 09:00.975
Damn.

09:01.018 --> 09:02.150
Is there any money in it?

09:02.193 --> 09:04.195
No.
Damn.

09:08.548 --> 09:10.593
[phone ringing]

09:10.637 --> 09:11.725
Hello?

09:11.768 --> 09:13.944
Hey, Brenda. It's Mary.

09:13.988 --> 09:16.207
Oh. Hey.

09:16.251 --> 09:19.907
Hi. I was just checking in,
seeing how you're doing.

09:21.561 --> 09:23.301
How am I doing about what?

09:24.912 --> 09:26.870
Well, I heard that Billy

09:26.914 --> 09:29.090
might be having
a tough time at school.

09:29.133 --> 09:31.179
Well, you know what, he'll be
fine, so thanks for calling.

09:31.222 --> 09:32.876
Okay.

09:32.920 --> 09:35.618
Um, if there's
anything I can do,

09:35.662 --> 09:37.533
or if you ever want to talk...?

09:37.577 --> 09:39.100
Good to know. Anything else?

09:39.143 --> 09:41.842
Uh, no, that was it.

09:41.885 --> 09:43.931
Okay. Bye.

09:45.889 --> 09:47.935
[dial tone]

09:48.979 --> 09:50.633
[exhales]

09:50.677 --> 09:52.287
[audience cheering on TV]

09:52.330 --> 09:54.855
ADULT SHELDON:
That night, my meemaw
was so inspired

09:54.898 --> 09:57.553
to be part
of our science experiment,

09:57.597 --> 09:59.903
she began working on it
as soon as she got home.

09:59.947 --> 10:00.948
♪

10:00.991 --> 10:02.210
♪ Fight till the end

10:02.253 --> 10:03.690
♪ 'Cause your life will depend

10:03.733 --> 10:05.779
♪ On the strength
that you have inside... ♪

10:05.822 --> 10:07.215
She was in the zone.

10:07.258 --> 10:08.259
♪ Standin' out in the crowd...

10:08.303 --> 10:09.783
She was focused.

10:09.826 --> 10:11.741
She was determined.

10:11.785 --> 10:14.657
She was also 68
and had eaten a lot of pizza.

10:14.701 --> 10:16.572
[snoring]

10:16.616 --> 10:21.229
ANNOUNCER: And the Nobel Prize for Science goes to Connie Tucker!

10:21.272 --> 10:22.883
[applause]♪ You're the best around...

10:22.926 --> 10:26.234
Oh, my goodness,
y'all are so sweet.

10:26.277 --> 10:27.801
[chuckles]

10:27.844 --> 10:31.587
I want to thank
my brilliant grandson Sheldon

10:31.631 --> 10:34.895
and his pal Dr. Linkletter,
for bringing me in

10:34.938 --> 10:36.679
on the experiment.

10:36.723 --> 10:39.595
I'd like to thank my Aunt Linda
for teaching me to crochet

10:39.639 --> 10:42.293
when I was knee-high
to a June bug.[laughter]

10:42.337 --> 10:46.341
And everyone, for making me...

10:46.384 --> 10:48.822
"The Meemaw of Science."

10:48.865 --> 10:52.826
[cheering, applause]♪ Oh, you're the best
around... ♪

10:52.869 --> 10:55.089
AUDIENCE [chanting]:
Meemaw! Meemaw! Meemaw!

10:55.132 --> 10:57.091
♪ You're the best around

10:57.134 --> 10:58.962
♪ Nothing's gonna ever
keep you... ♪

11:04.664 --> 11:06.317
ADULT SHELDON:
Being a good entrepreneur,

11:06.361 --> 11:09.973
my brother realized his supply
of my old tests was limited.

11:10.017 --> 11:13.803
So he did something else he was good at: lie to my father.

11:13.847 --> 11:16.284
Dad, you ever use the
copy room at school?

11:16.327 --> 11:18.112
Sometimes. Why?

11:18.155 --> 11:21.637
I need to make some copies for
a school project I'm working on.

11:21.681 --> 11:22.856
Uh, it's not really
for students.

11:22.899 --> 11:24.161
You know, they keep it locked.

11:24.205 --> 11:26.773
So, you have a key?

11:27.817 --> 11:29.645
I'm not giving you my key.

11:29.689 --> 11:31.342
Why not?Well, because I know you,

11:31.386 --> 11:33.214
and therefore don't trust you.

11:33.257 --> 11:35.695
I told you, it's for school.

11:35.738 --> 11:37.087
Great, then bring it
by my office tomorrow

11:37.131 --> 11:38.654
and I'll make copies.

11:38.698 --> 11:40.177
Never mind.

11:46.401 --> 11:48.098
It's not on my key chain!

11:48.142 --> 11:49.926
GEORGE JR.:
Dang it.

11:49.970 --> 11:52.886
ADULT SHELDON:
It was however,
in my dad's drawer at work,

11:52.929 --> 11:55.366
leading my brother
to do something

11:55.410 --> 11:58.935
he had never done before:
get to school early.

12:03.940 --> 12:05.725
Sucker.

12:06.856 --> 12:08.205
[machine whirring]

12:12.079 --> 12:14.821
It's like printing money.

12:15.865 --> 12:18.128
[key clicking in lock]

12:31.838 --> 12:32.969
[sniffs]

12:34.841 --> 12:36.277
[knocking on door]

12:40.237 --> 12:42.239
[door closes]

12:43.763 --> 12:45.068
You look beautiful.

12:45.112 --> 12:46.853
Shut up and kiss me.

12:49.116 --> 12:50.944
[moaning]GIVENS: Oh, Cheryl.

12:50.987 --> 12:52.859
HUTCHINS:
Oh, Hubert.

12:53.860 --> 12:55.035
[cow bellows]

12:55.078 --> 12:56.253
[phone ringing]

12:57.254 --> 12:59.082
John Sturgis.

12:59.126 --> 13:00.388
Hey, John.

13:00.431 --> 13:03.391
Connie.
So nice to hear from you.

13:03.434 --> 13:05.872
You'll never guess
what I'm doing.

13:05.915 --> 13:06.873
Tell me.

13:06.916 --> 13:08.962
I am working on a solar

13:09.005 --> 13:11.442
neutrino detector.

13:11.486 --> 13:15.882
Wow. I was gonna guess making
soft-boiled eggs. [chuckles]

13:15.925 --> 13:18.841
[chuckles]
Yeah, Sheldon and Linkletter

13:18.885 --> 13:20.277
asked me to help them out.

13:20.321 --> 13:23.803
Oh. Linkletter's involved.

13:23.846 --> 13:25.152
Oh, well, he's not so bad.

13:25.195 --> 13:27.197
[laughs]
You and he aren't...?

13:27.241 --> 13:29.983
Oh, no, no, no.
I'm still seeing Dale.

13:30.026 --> 13:31.767
Okay, good.

13:31.811 --> 13:34.509
I can handle you with a guy
who sells volleyballs,

13:34.552 --> 13:37.468
but you with another scientist,
that'd be like

13:37.512 --> 13:39.253
a dagger in the heart.

13:39.296 --> 13:41.864
[chuckles]
No daggers here.

13:41.908 --> 13:44.780
[chuckles] So tell me
about this experiment.

13:44.824 --> 13:47.870
Well, I don't know if you know
this, but solar neutrinos

13:47.914 --> 13:50.786
are like little messengers
from the center of the Sun.

13:50.830 --> 13:52.135
I did know that,

13:52.179 --> 13:54.355
but it's delightful
to hear you say it.

13:54.398 --> 13:57.880
Well, enjoy, 'cause that's about
all I remember.

13:57.924 --> 13:59.447
[laughs]

13:59.490 --> 14:01.231
So, what's new by you?Well, let's see...

14:01.275 --> 14:06.454
Uh, oh, yesterday I had
my first breakfast burrito.

14:06.497 --> 14:08.021
Mm.

14:08.064 --> 14:10.153
Good for you. How was it?

14:10.197 --> 14:14.244
Confusing. I ordinarily have
burritos for lunch or dinner.

14:14.288 --> 14:15.463
[Meemaw laughs]

14:15.506 --> 14:17.813
I don't know
how to respond to that.

14:17.857 --> 14:19.815
You're working on an experiment

14:19.859 --> 14:21.904
and I'm eating dinner
for breakfast.

14:21.948 --> 14:24.298
It's a crazy world.

14:24.341 --> 14:26.474
[moaning]

14:28.519 --> 14:30.304
I've got to get back
to the library.

14:30.347 --> 14:33.176
Oh, but this is so much
more fun than books.

14:33.220 --> 14:35.352
Will I be
seeing you tonight?

14:35.396 --> 14:38.921
Oh, you'll be seeing all of me.

14:38.965 --> 14:40.836
[both panting]

14:40.880 --> 14:42.969
I think this might be
my finest work.

14:43.012 --> 14:45.536
And she made my dinner
mittens, so that means a lot.

14:45.580 --> 14:47.408
Oh.

14:47.451 --> 14:48.888
I can't thank you enough.

14:48.931 --> 14:50.890
Shall we apply
the empirical method?

14:50.933 --> 14:53.196
Yes, the empirical method.
Let's apply that.

14:53.240 --> 14:55.242
[knocking on door]

14:56.547 --> 14:58.985
What now?

14:59.028 --> 15:01.161
I feel like I might've
overstepped my bounds

15:01.204 --> 15:05.252
last night, so I just wanted to
bring you these and apologize.

15:06.906 --> 15:07.994
Thank you.

15:09.038 --> 15:10.213
And I did mean it.

15:10.257 --> 15:11.954
If you ever need to talk,
I'm here.

15:11.998 --> 15:13.869
Appreciate it.

15:13.913 --> 15:15.131
Okay.

15:17.351 --> 15:18.526
It's more than Billy.

15:22.356 --> 15:24.314
Herschel moved out.

15:26.012 --> 15:29.015
Oh, Brenda, I'm so sorry.

15:30.407 --> 15:32.018
Do you want to come in?

15:34.063 --> 15:35.456
Of course.

15:42.942 --> 15:44.682
So what's with the box?

15:44.726 --> 15:47.163
SHELDON:
The experiment needs to be
in complete darkness to work.

15:47.207 --> 15:49.078
We watch these monitors
for the results.

15:53.039 --> 15:55.911
Okay, all that's left
is to turn on the cameras.

15:55.955 --> 15:57.260
Sheldon, will you
get the lights?

15:57.304 --> 15:59.219
Yes, sir.

15:59.262 --> 16:01.612
Is that to make it
more dramatic?

16:01.656 --> 16:04.615
It's so that we can better
see the flashes on the monitor.

16:04.659 --> 16:06.139
But a little drama never hurts.

16:06.182 --> 16:07.618
[chuckles]All right, here we go.

16:07.662 --> 16:10.056
Commencement of the solar
neutrino detector prototype

16:10.099 --> 16:13.059
in three, two, one.

16:13.102 --> 16:14.974
[whirring]

16:20.240 --> 16:21.415
I don't see anything.

16:21.458 --> 16:22.720
Give it a moment.

16:27.987 --> 16:30.467
♪

16:30.511 --> 16:31.947
Is that it?

16:31.991 --> 16:33.035
That's it.

16:33.079 --> 16:34.297
[gasps]

16:34.341 --> 16:35.951
We did it.

16:35.995 --> 16:37.431
Phase one is a success.

16:37.474 --> 16:38.954
Congratulations.

16:38.998 --> 16:40.260
MEEMAW:
Wow.

16:40.303 --> 16:43.959
Look at those
beautiful neutrinos.

16:44.003 --> 16:45.178
Those aren't neutrinos.

16:45.221 --> 16:46.440
What are you talking about?

16:46.483 --> 16:48.007
That's what we're looking for.

16:48.050 --> 16:50.009
That's just radioactivity.

16:50.052 --> 16:53.969
Well, then,
when do we find the neutrinos?

16:54.013 --> 16:56.232
We don't.
This is just the prototype.

16:56.276 --> 16:57.712
You kidding me?

16:57.755 --> 17:00.193
The actual device needed
would be the size of a building.

17:00.236 --> 17:02.064
And that's 20 to 30 years away.

17:02.108 --> 17:04.066
Well, I could be dead by then.

17:04.110 --> 17:06.460
You still may have
helped advance science.

17:06.503 --> 17:08.070
Unless another team
beats us to it.

17:08.114 --> 17:09.071
Yeah.

17:10.246 --> 17:12.422
I'm gonna wait in the car.

17:12.466 --> 17:15.556
If it helps, in 30 years,
I should still be alive.

17:17.253 --> 17:19.690
Boy, you'd think
she'd be happy about that.

17:19.734 --> 17:20.561
[door closes]

17:25.218 --> 17:27.002
Remember, the smart cheater
gets some answers wrong.

17:31.746 --> 17:32.964
I heard I might find you here.

17:34.009 --> 17:36.098
Oh, hey, Mr. Givens.

17:36.142 --> 17:38.796
Would you like to explain why
this was on the copy machine?

17:39.841 --> 17:41.451
Anyone could have
left that there.

17:41.495 --> 17:43.758
It's your brother's
and Tam said it was you.

17:44.802 --> 17:46.456
Fine, but I only left it there

17:46.500 --> 17:48.719
because you came in
the copy room and I had to hide.

17:49.807 --> 17:51.722
What? When? What?

17:51.766 --> 17:53.768
This morning before school.

17:53.811 --> 17:55.552
[exhales]:
Uh...

17:55.596 --> 17:57.598
What exactly did you see?

17:57.641 --> 17:59.600
I don't want to talk about it.

17:59.643 --> 18:02.124
Well, I don't want you
talking about it.

18:02.168 --> 18:03.995
Well, I don't want
you talking about this.

18:04.039 --> 18:05.954
I don't even know what this is.

18:05.997 --> 18:07.129
I don't even know what I saw.

18:07.173 --> 18:08.913
All right, then.
All right.

